Organization = {IEEE; IEEE Comp Soc; IEEE Tech Comm Engn Comp Based Syst (ECBS); IEEE
   Tech Comm Engn Autonom \& Autonomous Syst; RT-RK LLC Comp Based Syst;
   Univ Studiorum},
Abstract = {The agile paradigm is now a mainstream approach to software development,
   with Scrum emerging as the dominant methodology in the field. The rapid
   diffusion of the approach is an indicator of its current value to
   organizations but further gains seem possible. One major step would be
   the use of the agile approach in all organizational activity. This
   opportunity has always been part of the Scrum philosophy but few have
   attempted to put it into practice so far. The purpose of this paper is
   to consider what is involved, proposing a hierarchical Scrum model to
   make it suitable for such wider use. The proposal draws on established
   ideas from both Soft Systems Methodology (SSM) and Deming's
   Plan-Do-Study-Act (PDSA) cycle. The new model also has the potential to
