Abstract = {In the last decade there has been increasing interest in pair
   programming. However, despite work has been done, there is still a lack
   of substantial evidence of pair programming effects in industrial
   environments. To increase a body of evidence regarding the real benefits
   of pair programming, we investigate its relationship with software
   detects. The analysis is based on 14-months data collected from a large
   Italian manufacturing company. The team of 17 developers adopted a
   customized version of extreme programming and used pair programming on a
   daily basis. We explore and compare the defect rate of the code changed
   by doing pair and solo programming. The results show that defects appear
   to be lower for the code modified during pair programming. As a
